## üé® COLOR USAGE BEST PRACTICES (Official Databricks Guidelines)

### ‚úÖ DO: Balanced & Intentional Color Usage

**Use tints and shades of analogous colors to add depth:**
- Combine different shades of the same color family for visual hierarchy
- Example: Navy-900 (text) + Navy-700 (borders) + Navy-100 (backgrounds)
- Example: Lava-600 (critical) + Lava-500 (high) + Lava-100 (highlights)
- Creates balanced, cohesive compositions with intentional color choices

**Approved Color Combinations:**
```
‚úÖ Navy-900 text on White background (highest contrast)
‚úÖ Navy-900 text on Oat-light background
‚úÖ White text on Blue-600 background
‚úÖ White text on Navy-700 background
‚úÖ White text on Lava-600 background
‚úÖ Blue-600 on Oat-light background (cards, borders)
‚úÖ Navy-700 headers with White text
```

### ‚ùå DON'T: Low Contrast Text

**NEVER use colored text on backgrounds that produce low contrast:**
- ‚ùå Light yellow text on white background - FAILS contrast
- ‚ùå Teal text on dark teal background - FAILS contrast
- ‚ùå Pink text on light pink background - FAILS contrast
- ‚ùå Light gray text on white background - FAILS contrast

**Readability is critical. Always follow WCAG accessibility standards:**
- **Minimum contrast ratio:** 4.5:1 for normal text
- **Minimum contrast ratio:** 3:1 for large text (18px+)
- Test all text/background combinations with contrast checker tools

### ‚ùå DON'T: Mix Colors with Similar Brightness

**Avoid mixing colors with low contrast due to similar brightness levels:**
- ‚ùå Dark red circle on green background - similar brightness
- ‚ùå Coral circle on yellow/orange background - similar brightness
- ‚ùå Light gray circle on light pink background - similar brightness
- ‚ùå Muted purple circle on muted blue background - similar brightness

**High contrast is your friend when mixing different hues:**
- ‚úÖ Use dark colors on light backgrounds
- ‚úÖ Use light colors on dark backgrounds
- ‚úÖ Avoid mid-tone on mid-tone combinations
- ‚úÖ Test perceived brightness, not just hue

